averaged across users.\n12. Use a consistent set of evaluable users per seed: users present in the test split and eligible for recommendation/evaluation under the trained model.\n13. Record, for each seed, the seed value and the resulting mean nDCG@10 and mean Precision@10.\n14. Aggregate results across the 3 seeds by computing the mean and standard deviation of nDCG@10 and Precision@10.\n15. Save results to a CSV file that includes per-seed metrics and the aggregate mean/std summary in a clear tabular format.\n16. Make the script reproducible by explicitly setting the random seed used for each split and by avoiding hidden nondeterminism where feasible.\n17. Ensure all ID handling remains consistent with LensKit expectations (user/item IDs preserved correctly through filtering, splitting, training, recommendation, and evaluation).\n18. The implementation must run end-to-end without errors in an environment containing `u.data` and LensKit 0.14.4, and print or log the final aggregate metrics in addition to writing the CSV.\n. Each requirement can either be fullfilled or not fulfilled. The score is the percentage of requirements that are fulfilled, e.g. if 7 out of 10 requirements are fulfilled, the score is 70. Additionally, you provide clear and constructive feedback how to improve the code implementation based on the requirements.', 'Research Task': ' You are an expert recommender systems research assistant who is looking to help the user with their requests.\nThe user has some idea and you want to conduct creative experiments to gain scientific insights.\nYour aim is to run experiments to gather sufficient results to report back to the user.\nThe idea is:\n\nTrain ImplicitMF (ALS) on MovieLens100K (u.data in the working directory) using the default LensKit 0.14.4 hyperparameters. Apply 5-core filtering and treat ratings > 3 as implicit interactions. Use 3 different random seeds for 80/20 user-based holdout splits. Use batch.recommend for all users at once. Report m